                  , two 10 l., one 5 l., and three 1 l. Bank notes, his property
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18200918-264-person2472">
                  HENRY 
                  FIELDING CORFE
               <interp inst="t18200918-264-person2472" type="surname" value="FIELDING CORFE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200918-264-person2472" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200918-264-person2472" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I <rs id="t18200918-264-viclabel1513" type="occupation">keep a school</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18200918-264-victim2471 t18200918-264-viclabel1513"></join> at New Church, Isle of Wight. On the 6th of July I lodged at the Nag's Head, James-street, Covent-garden. About half-past eleven o'clock at night I was going to my lodgings, the prisoners accosted me in Brydges-street, and solicited something to drink. I wished them to pursue a better course, Smith said she should be very happy to do so, but was afraid her friends would not take her back. I walked with them, conversing on that subject, and then went to their lodgings in a court near the Theatre, I might have remained there three or four hours. I sat on the bed, and being particularly tired, I fell asleep - Byrne had left me with Smith. I had taken my coat off, the notes were in the pocket. I awoke about four o'clock, and missed them, Smith was then gone. I got Gooding, and we found the prisoners together in Wych-street - I am certain they are the women - we secured them, and took them to a house. As Gooding was going up stairs with Smith, something fell from her; we called for a light, and found, a half handkerchief lying on the ground, containing my notes; they have my writing on them. We charged her with dropping them; she cried, but said nothing.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182009180098"></xptr>Cross-examined by MR. BARRY. Q. How long did your moral lecture continue - A. I do not know; I merely accompanied her home. I was quite sober. I am a married man.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18200918-264-person2473">
                  THOMAS 
                  GOODING
               <interp inst="t18200918-264-person2473" type="surname" value="GOODING"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200918-264-person2473" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18200918-264-person2473" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I went with Mr. Corfe, and took the prisoner in Wych-street. I took Smith, and he took Byrne. As I was taking Smith up stairs in a coffee-shop, something fell from her. I found the handkerchief, containing two 10 l., one 5 l., and one 1 l. note, with three half-crowns and one shilling. She said she was sorry for it, and hoped he would forgive her.</p>
               <p>SMITH - <rs id="t18200918-264-verdict1514" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18200918-264-verdict1514" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 16.</p>
